On 5-2-18, Univar USA picked up 3 55 gallon metal open top drums of waste Acrylamide from Boasso in Chalmette, LA.  The waste was transported to our yard in Geismar LA, pending shipment to the TSDF Tradebe.  On 5-4-18 at 6:16PM pressure had built up inside the drum to the point that it ruptured, blew the lid out of the ring and created a large amount of smoke.  The drum lip appears to have deformed under pressure, allowing the pressure to release, and the lid to come off the drum.

XPO Logistics contacted ERTS in regard to a release of 5-lbs of Hazardous, UN1823, Caustic Soda Pearls (Sodium Hydroxide) that occurred on 05/04/2018 at 0120 EST. It was reported that during unloading operations, skids that were placed too close to one another, upon pulling one skid out the skid scraped and tore the (1) 50-lb paper bag and released product onto Trailer #3176932. ERTS determined that, due to the caustic nature of the chemical, XPO terminal does not have the proper poly container to dispose of this waste per regulation and a contractor was dispatched on-site. Contractor confirmed that (1) 50-lb paper bag released approximately 5-lb of product onto the trailer floor. Contractor stated that they cleaned up the spill and placed the debris and the bag into a (1) 55-gallon poly drum and disposed on-site per XPO regulation. Titan labels were generated. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by this incident and so no additional reporting is required.

ERTS was notified by XPO Logistics of a release of 1qt of UN1993 Flammable liquid, n.o.s. from a 330gal poly tote on trailer 435378. The cause was due to improper loading at the customers location. The cap to the tote was not properly tightened. ERTS reviewed the SDS with terminal personnel who will clean the release with absorbents and proper PPE. Terminal personnel will place the waste into a 10gal metal pail in the facilities waste area. Terminal stated they will call the shipper to tighten the cap on the tote, and will ship on to the costumer. All waste was left at the terminal.

XPO contacted ERTS in regard to a release of 0.5 gallons of Hazardous, UN1824, Sunrise Scale-X that occurred on 05/01/2018 at 0105 EST. XPO Terminal personnel reported that (1) box containing (4) 1-gallon plastic bottles were not properly braced during loading at previous terminal and during transit the box fell to floor of Trailer #3133326 and busted 1 out of 4 bottles. XPO terminal personnel examined the remaining bottles to determine if they are undamaged and can be shipped on to consignee. XPO was capable of containing the spill and they placed vinegar down for a neutralizing product and then utilized absorbent material for cleaning. XPO terminal personnel placed the damaged box and the absorbent debris into a 10-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged on-site per XPO regulation.

column42: BUTADIENES, STABILIZED OR BUTADIENES AND HYDROCARBON MIXTURE, STABILIZED CONTAINING MORE THAN 40% BUTADIENES
column168: On 05/03/2018, at 0928 hours, a Federal Railroad Administration Hazardous Materials Inspector in the CSX Clinton Yard discovered ACFX 220477, a residue tank car of Butadienes, leaking from the vapor line valve. The car was isolated and National Response Center and Shipper were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2018-0504-00111). SUNPRO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve in the open position and the secondary closure plug improperly installed. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Ms. Tami Morgan, phone 330-374-2986. Contractor personnel closed the valve and properly installed the secondary closure plug. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 386 NARRI: 47

Transfer was made and product returned to the shipper.  The cargo tank trailer was found to have a crack in the shell at the 9th ring stiffener of 10, at approximately the 7 o'clock position,left side, just to the left front of the trailer tandem frame rail.

column17: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: AT 20:51 HRS ON 5/2/2018, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY'S (KCS) ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT RECEIVED NOTICE THAT ACFX 94713 (UN1832, CLASS 8, SULFURIC ACID, SPENT) WAS LWAKING FROM THE MANWAY COVER IN ITS PORT ARTHUR, TX RAIL YARD. A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DEPLOYED TO INVESTIGATE AND SECURE THE TANK CAR. UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONDER FOUND THAT THE LIQUID LINE PLUG WAS UNSECURED. TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED TO THE PLUG, AND THEN THE PLUG WAS INSTALLED TOOL TIGHT. THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED PRIOR TO THE BEING RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: XPO contacted ERTS in regard to a release of an unknown amount of a Hazardous, UN2811, Organic Toxic solid that occurred on 05/14/2018 at 2230 EST. XPO reported that during loading procedures, at the previous terminal, a (1) cardboard box was damaged and attempted to have been patched. The patch was unsuccessful and Trailer #4652008 arrived at LHW terminal with a powder substance that impacted the trailer floor and other freight. Due to the toxicity of the product (located on the BOL) and immediately reached out to ERTS. Contractor arrived on-site at XPO logistics. Contractor verified that upon initial inspection, approximately 1 cup of product was released. Contractor stated the impacted areas were the trailer floor and other freight close in proximity. Contractor also stated that the damaged material was punctured by a forklift and that the pallets were double stacked when they were not supposed to be. Incident looks to be due to improper loading. Contractor updated that waste was contain in (1) 55-gallon poly drum; (2) damaged boxes of material along with swept debris. (1) 55-gallon tripled lined metal drum.  All waste was staged on-site per XPO regulations.   There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by this incident and so no additional reporting is required.

NOTED DOT NON-FLAMMABLE GAS LABEL AND CONTENTS LABEL ,20 LB CO2 EXTINGUISHER ON BOX. FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR NON-FLAMMABLE GAS 2.2 . MOVE LEAKING PACKAGE TO OUTDOOR AREA, USED ORANGE CONE TO ISOLATE PACKAGE UNTIL FIRE EXTINGUISHER WAS EMPTY/STOPPED LEAKING. INSPECTED CARBON DIOXIDE EXTINGUISHER, FOUND ACTIVATING HANDLE AND SAFETY PIN BENT. REVIEW OF WHAT CAUSED PACKAGE DAMAGE: PACKAGE WAS PLACED ON UNLOAD DOOR SLIDE WITH IRREGULARS AND OVERWEIGHT PACKAGES. IMPACT OF OVERWEIGHT PACKAGES DAMAGED BOX AND BENT ACTIVATION HANDLE AND SAFETY PIN, THEREBY CAUSING FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO DISCHARGE.

column168: TCKU 478197 was discovered at the Elwood, Ill LPC leaking liquid. The placard for the container was UN3266 Corrosive. Our response contractor Sunpro was called out to clean up the spill. column168: THE PRE-LOADER FOR PACKAGE CAR 614 REMOVED THE HAZMAT BOX (WEIGHT 39.4 LBS) FROM THE MIDDLE GREEN BOXLINE CAGE. UPON MY INITIAL RESPONSE, AFTER CONSULTING THE CURRENT DECISION TREE, I WENT TO THE APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET (CORROSIVE). THE APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET PROVIDED ME THE PERSONAL PROTECTION EQUIPMENT REQUIREMENTS AND AFTER GEARING UP I WENT TO THE PACKAGE. AFTER DOING THE PH TEST, I APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE UNTIL THE PH TEST READ BETWEEN 6-9 RANGE. UPON OPENING THE BOX I DISCOVERED ONE BOTTLE OF 4 WITHOUT IT'S PLASTIC SCREW ON CAP. LIQUID HAD SPREAD AND SOILED ALL FOUR SIMILAR BOTTLES. AFTER FOLLOWING THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET CLEAN UP INSTRUCTIONS I QUESTIONED THE ONLY WITNESS PRE-LOADER. I MUST SPECULATE THE FOLLOWING CHAIN OF EVENTS. THE PRE-LOADER STATED THAT IT DID NOT LEAK WHEN REMOVED FROM THE BOXLINE CAGE. IT ONLY STARTED TO LEAK AFTER PLACEMENT IN THE REAR DOOR OF THE VEHICLE. IT IS MY ASSUMPTION THAT THE BOX WAS DROPPED FROM WAIST HEIGHT TO THE FLOOR POPPING THE CAP OFF.
column169: THE PRE-LOADERS IN THE SANTA ANITA CENTER WILL BE RETRAINED IN PROPER PACKAGE HANDLING. THE SAFETY IN USING "HAND TO SURFACE" METHODS FOR ALL PACKAGES. column168: A box truck containing hazardous waste arrived at the Clean Harbors La Porte, Texas facility for an offload. While off-loading, facility personnel noticed a leaking metal drum container. A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and unloaded the leaking drum. The leaking drum was packed into a salvage drum by the response crew, and the floor of the truck’s cargo area was cleaned and returned to service.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The release was the direct result of improper container selection and preparation. The driver has been retrained on proper container inspection, selection and preparation for corrosive waste streams. The driver has been instructed that improperly packaged hazardous materials must be rejected for transportation or repackaged into appropriately rated containers. The shipper was notified and advised to use an appropriate UN rated container for shipments of corrosive wastes. The shipper has also been instructed to properly package wastes before scheduling to have wastes picked up for proper disposal.

column168: XPO contacted ERTS in regard to a release of an unknown amount of a paint related material. It was reported that when Trailer #3111162 pulled into XPO terminal, there was a noticeable leak that was slowly coming out of the trailer and onto the yard. XPO personnel left the trailer on to the yard and immediately notified ERTS.  Contractor reported that the products that leaked changed from the original call. Steel Spec Universal Primer UN1263 originated from (10) 5-gallon metal pail that were stacked 3 high. Contractor noticed a grey primer and that was due to a leak of product Protective Marine Coatings (General polymers GP-3569A56 Part A Silver Grey) originating from inside a (1) 5-gallon pail due to the corner of a broken pallet puncturing the pail.  Contractor estimates that (4) 5-gallon metal pails were damaged releasing approximately 13-gallons. Contractor has generated (8) 55-gallon metal drums of waste for XPO to manage disposition. All waste was staged on-site per XPO regulation.
DURING SECURITY SEARCH IT WAS FOUND THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS A BATTERY. BATTERY APPEARS TO BE EXCEPTED UNDER A67 - HOWEVER THE REQUIRED INFORMATION WAS NOT INDICATED ON THE AWB AS REGULATOINS REQUIRE.

Approximately 1g of UN1325 was on the trailer floor when door was opened to unload. Appears to have been punctured at prior transfer due to skids being slammed into the side of the fiberboard base. Reported to Safety and Security prior to unloading as the flammable solid has a flash point that's unsafe. Per safety and security instructions from tyler shook, damaged drum was recouped and put into a recovery drum.
column169: Recommendations are to carefully adhere to load procedures at the DC's to ensure spills don't occur in transit.

column168: While making a delivery to Town of Nederland , the straps on an IBC containing sodium hydroxide solution slipped causing it to fall off the truck and break.  The contents of the tote were released onto the roadway.  DPC contacted waste remediation contractor, Environmental Restoration, to clean up the area.  CDPHE was contacted of incident.    Once it was determined the RQ had been exceeded, NRC was called.  The clean-up operations were already initiated.  Spill was contained and did not impact nearby waterway.    At spill site, Environmental Restoration met with state and local regulators as well as the fire department to determine the scope of work.  It started to rain about 4 pm so the team begins neutralizing spill area with citric acid.  The roadway was rinsed with water and collected in vac truck.  Soil and gravel in impacted area was collected for disposal.  Random samples were tested with strips to confirm pH of 7.    Collected material will be disposed of by Badger Daylighting.  DPC has requested copies of manifests for their files.  Approximately 200-gallons of neutralized caustic soda solution and soil slurry sent for disposal.    There were no injuries.

column168: On May 19, 2018 at approx. 1:00am, a smell of gas was reported at the S. Portland Rigby railyard. The responding emergency crews located the leak by sense of smell, audible hiss of releasing product, and visual indicators of a liquid propane leak. Terminal operator Jordan Ellsworth was contacted and reported to the terminal. After a discussion with the emergency responders, the terminal operator and two members of the fire department were allowed to access the rail car. Upon ascending to the top of the tank car and opening the protective housing cover, a liquid valve was viewed leaking on railcar UTLX956600. The valve type was a Midland 720 or 721 series valve. The secondary closure (threaded steel plug) was in place and tool tight. A review of the plug identified multiple layers of Teflon tape on a portion of the plug threads. During mitigation of the event, Operator Jordan Ellsworth confirmed securement of the plug by placing a physical exertion on the plug. It was confirmed that the plug was tool tight in accordance with the regulations and this action was witnessed by two members of the emergency response team. It is suspected that the valve may have an internal failure and the product was leaking past the closed valve and the taped portion of the plug.
column169: After a review of the release, it was determined that a consideration that may prevent future leaks on the threaded portion on the steel plug is to ensure that the threads of the plug valve are clear of any potential obstructions such as multiple tape layers. This action can be performed by removing old tape, brushing the threads as appropriate if necessary and the application of new tape OR appropriate thread dope which is product compatible for propane. Furthermore, it would suggested that employees who are trained and qualified to perform product transfer on rail cars review appropriate policies, procedures, or training materials that will demonstrate the appropriate actions.

column168: Driver was preparing to depart from the Gateway Travel Plaza at 2615 NW Stallings Dr, Nacogdoches, TX 75964.  While conducting the pre-trip load inspection, the driver discovered liquid dripping out of the front end of the trailer. The driver called the internal Emergency Operations Center to alert of the in-transit release and an Emergency Response team was dispatched to the site. The response team arrived at the site, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and unloaded the leaking drum.  Emergency Response Report states a 55 gallon drum breached at the bottom of the drum due to corrosion.  The drum was over packed into a properly rated salvage drum for continued transportation to the final disposal facility. The truck floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service. The Texas Commission on Environmental Quality was notified, no report number provided.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. This release was the direct result of compromised container integrity due to a grosse amount of external corrosion. The shipper was notified and advised to use an appropriate container for future shipments of this waste stream, as well as discontinuing use of corroded containers.

On May 18, 2018,  XPO Logistics (XAB Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1760, AlphaPrep PC-7030, 8, PG II (PRO#114918355) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel discovered (1) 55-gallon poly drum of product to be leaking from the cap. Approximately 0.25 gallon of product has been released to the top of the drum. 1124 ERTS notified Chemtrec per the Bill of Lading. Monica McMillan took receipt of the call and assigned report number 2018051800142 to the incident. 1144 ERTS contacted the shipper to obtain an SDS. 1214 Following a review of the incident and the reported material involved, ERTS has obtained and reviewed the MSDS with the caller. The terminal personnel stated that they are capable, confident and able to clean the release and will wear the provided PPE and over pack the damaged freight into a 85-gallon poly drum in OS & D. 1220 XPO Logistics indicated that they no longer feel confident in over-packing the damaged drum. Contractor indicated that the drum had a faulty bung. Contractor replaced the bung and sloshed the drum to make sure no further release. Contractor indicated that approximately 1-cup of product was released. Contractor wiped down the drum with a neutralized the drum with soda ash and water. Contractor has finished cleanup activities. Contractor generated (1) 5-gallon poly drum of neutralized absorbent materials for waste to be staged in OS & D for XPO to manage disposition.

As the employees were off loading the container at the loading dock in Bristol, CT it was found that the container was leaking.  The employee's immediately contained the spill.  It was determined the bottles that were packed inside the container were not sitting upright, causing the contents to leak out.  The bottles were re-packaged, the spill area was cleaned up and the damaged container and the cleanup material  was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.

Palmetto State Transportation's, LLC contacted ERTS regarding a cargo release. ERTS coordinated with Environmental Solutions, Inc. (ESI) to respond to the site for proper cleanup activities. ESI arrived on site and confirmed the release to be from 1-55 gallon poly drum due to a loose bung on the drum releasing 2 cups UN2922 to the trailer floor and underlying parking area. Contractor has tightened the lid on the drum and has properly re-secured it and shrink wrapped both drums on the skid. Contractor hand dug the impacted area and containerized the dirt and spent absorbents into 1-55 gallon poly drum. Contractor transported the generated waste off site for proper disposal.

On May 5, 2018 while shoving cars towards the hump in Moorman yard the coupling on an open gondola car (SOU65705) bypassed the coupler on SHPX206736. Tank car SHPX206736 lost its entire load of alcohols, n.o.s. and ignited. column168: A passenger vehicle traveling in front of the transport vehicle began turning right off of the roadway and, at the last second, turned back onto the highway to turn in a different direction. The fuel transport driver attempted to avoid a collision by maneuvering around the vehicle, and in doing so, made contact with the passenger vehicle and then overturned. The tank caught fire upon overturning and the driver was trapped inside. Passersby rescued the driver before the truck and trailer were fully engulfed in flames. When this incident was reported, an environmental clean-up group were called to respond to remove fuel that had not burned and to secure the area to reduce environmental impact. The burned tractor-trailer were removed by a towing company and the highway department was on scene to determine what actions would be necessary to open the roadway.

column168: When unloading freight from trailer forklift operator punctured a tote that was in front of another shipment he was handling with the forkblades of the forklift he was operating puncturing the tote and contributing to the unintentional release. Immediately internal Hazwoper personnel at facility took empty recovery drums and placed out under the trailer to start recovering the spilled material. Boom, sand, absorbent pads and oil-dri were put into place to help contain spilled material. Our third party spill response contractor was called who dispatched a local spill response company. Over the course of several days the cleanup company was onsite cleaning the spilled material with absorbents, vac truck. Some soil in a swale was impacted which was removed by excavation and replaced with new soil and rip rap stone.
column169: Our forklift operators need to pay attention to the clearances of their forkblades when unloading freight to prevent these types of events from occurring. Putting dunnage such as a pallet in between the IBC and other freight can also help to prevent these types of events.

column168: It was reported that due to a forklift puncture, 1-55 gallon steel drum was impacted causing the release of an estimated 7 gallons UN1993, Mclube 1804h Lubricant to the floor of trailer #3112758 and the underlying parking area. ERTS dispatched a contractor, GEC Environmental, who confirmed the incident to be due to a forklift puncture. GEC Environmental over-packed the impacted drum into 1-95 gallon drum and containerized all spent absorbents into 1-55 gallon poly drum. All waste was staged on site for XPO Logistics personnel to manage disposal.

Shortly after our driver departed, the shipper noticed a puddle of HazMat.  They called the carrier, who contacted the CMTV driver, who stopped the CTMV.  The driver climbed the CTMV's ladder, found a remote-actuated vapor vent valve was not fully closed, despite the actuator indicator showing it closed.  The vapor vent valve is a 3" ball valve, which, upon very close inspection, he noticed was just slightly open.  He manually closed the valve.  We estimate the HazMat only released briefly due to movement related surging, however, about one hour elapsed from when the driver first moved the CTMV and when he closed the valve.  Our Reference No. 69111
column169: This CTMV is equipped with a safety system that allows the top-mounted vent valve to be remotely operated using a ground level control.  In this incident, the remote-actuator was loose and became mis-aligned with the ball valve that it actuates.  Consequently, the actuator was not always able to fully drive the valve to the closed position.  We recommend DOT share this lesson learned.

column168: On May 31, 2018, XPO Logistics (ULB Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1950, Johnsen's Non-Chlorinated Brake Parts Cleaner, 2.1 (PRO#416007340) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel discovered (1) box containing (12) 13-ounces aerosol cans to be crushed due to an unknown cause. Approximately 13-ounces of product was released from (1) 13-ounce can to the box and dock floor. Following a review of the incident and the reported material involved, ERTS has obtained and reviewed the MSDS with the caller. The terminal personnel stated that they are capable, confident and able to clean the release and will wear the provided PPE and over pack the damaged freight into a 10-gallon metal drum in OS & D.
column172: Cylindrical metal container, not for compressed gases (i. e., not a pressure vessel)

column168: It was reported at 0230 ET, terminal personnel went to unload trailer #3111144 (inbound from NIO) when they discovered one 600 lb of UN1017 Chlorine Gas was leaking at an unknown rate due to an unknown cause, the trailer door was closed immediately and ERTS was notified at 0530 ET. ERTS then contacted HEPACO for a response. HEPACO arrived on site and donned the appropriate PPE and entered the trailer with a meter. The cylinder was further inspected and determined that the seal around the stem was bad / defective. HEPACO applied an A Cap from a chlorine kit on the valve to stop the release. The cylinder was secured and left on site for XPO Logistics terminal personnel to manage.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

The truck trailer carrying the liquid totes with the cleaning compound was taking the ramp from Texas 161 South into Texas 183 West which ramp was not posted for any advised safe speed on a ramp and was uneven (flattened in the turn) and this led  the trailer lean/tilt into the left side during taking the ramp to the right., leading towards route  183 West in Irving, TX. This cause the ramp to be blocked for around 10 hours. The incident was reported immediately to Chemtrec. There were no other participants in the incident such as other vehicles or pedestrians. The shipper was immediately informed as well, and Irving, TX Fire Department was at the scene in 2 minutes. There were no injuries on the scene. After the opening of the trailer it was discovered, that a very small amount of the cargo (cleaning compound) was released in the trailer due to the liquid tote been on its side and about 20 gallons leaked through the cab. The liquid totes were slightly deformed but were not licking at all, except for 1 that was lifted up and stopped the leakage. Later on the cargo was taken out of the trailer by the Irving Fire Department crew and reloaded to a different trailer and safely transported back to the shipper.
column169: Partially the cause of the tilt was that some of the liquid totes were half full and created strong search causing the liquid to splash into the tote making the transportation unstable. The load was secured and after the opening of the trailer was discovered that cargo was at same positions as it was loaded and that points to the extra liquid search being the main cause of the incident.  Also it was mentioned by the Fire Department that this particular ramp does not have the right amount of tilt in turn to help vehicles enter, proceed and exit through the ramp, as needed. And did not have posted safe speed limit on the ramp. Also Irving Fire Department officials mentioned that similar incidents had happened before at those ramp.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: GAMX 2543 was discovered producing an odor by BNSF train yard personnel.  BNSF local Hazmat Responder investigated and confirmed vapor being released at the re-closing pressure relief device.  Upon disassembly the serviceable part of the PRD, the responder found the main shaft of the valve to be loose.  It was determined that the spring was broken, or had loosened to the point it could not hold a vapor tight seal under normal atmospheric conditions.  Car was held for replacement/repair of PRD by an authorized mobile tank car repair resource.  Current status is the valve has been removed and outlet has been capped with a blind flange while parts for repair are procured.  Applicable OTMA may be applied for upon completion of the work.  This was a vapor dispersion only, no environmental contamination or clean up required.
column169: Ensure adequate pre-trip inspection completed prior to release of DOT package into transportation.  Review procedures and re-train personnel associated with load/unload/pre-trip process to verify training is up to standard and spot audit for compliance.

column168: GATX 61215 was reported emanting vapors in the Somerville, TX yard on 5/24/2018.  The BNSF Responder inspected the car and determined the release was coming from GATX 61215 Salco rupture disk assembly flange.  The Salco rupture disk assembly four bolts were found to be less than tool tight allowing product to be released when the car was in movement.  The responder properly tightened the four rupture disk assembly bolts to mitigate the release.
column169: Ensure the shippers pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and verified as it pertains to loading and the securement of tank cars

column168: On May 24, 2018 personnel in the CSXT Russell KY yard reported GATX 62629, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid was suspected to be leaking from the top of car.  The car was isolated and Arkema was notified via CHEMTREC Report # 2018-05-24-00038.  Quick Response, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car was leaking from the pressure release vent (PRV) due to multiple broken/missing components of the PRV: broken threads on the frangible disc retaining ring, frangible disc not installed, frangible disc retaining ring not install, broken threads on frangible disc base assembly, surge protection insert gasket not installed.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative – Garrick Ramage.  Contractor personnel made emergency repairs to the PRV to secure the release.  The car was set out of transportation pending additional repairs by a certified mobile repair facility.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: The driver, Edward Aaron Smith, actually missed his turn off of Highway 69.  So as he was coming into the intersection at Upper River Road and Indian Hills he decided to make a right turn and eventually circle back around to the highway.  When Mr. Smith made the turn the trailer tires ran off the roadway into a deep ditch on the right side.  The steep downward angle of the ditch caused the vehicle to overturn.  Fuel spilled from the tanker into the drainage ditch to the right of the road.  Morgan County EMA was contacted and came to assist with clean up.  They were able to contain the spill with absorbent material and foam.   McBrayer Trucking was contacted immediately and within approximately an hour and a half, the owner Bobby McBrayer was on site to pump gasoline and diesel from the overturned tanker into a working tanker.  The fuel was then taken to Petroleum Sales Inc and pumped into their tanks.  Clean Harbor company was contacted and came and did the onsite clean up.  We are still waiting to find out damage amounts and clean up amounts.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: ERTS received a call from XPO Logistics, Terminal XLA, concerning a spill of 5 gallons of a Hazardous, UN3082, Dibutyl Phthalate. It was reported by XPO, that during loading procedures, a forklift punctured a (1) 55-gallon metal drum that released contents onto dock#81. There were no drains or waterways impacted by this spill and so no further reporting is required. ERTS dispatched a contractor on site to aid in providing more information about the product released, contain the spill and assess the impacted area.  Contractor indicated that approximately 2-gallons of product was released to a 3' x 3' area of the dock floor. Contractor utilized absorbent materials to clean the release. Contractor has over-packed the damaged drum into a 95-gallon poly drum and the cleanup debris was placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. All waste has been staged in OS & D for XPO to manage disposition.

XPO reported that 10oz of hazardous, UN2796 battery acid released from 2 batteries onto trailer due to improper loading.  Terminal personnel cleaned the release donning the proper PPE and utilizing baking soda.  Terminal personnel placed the waste and damaged batteries into (2) 10-gal poly drums.  All waste was staged on site.

column168: On May 28, 2018 at 1630 hours, personnel at CSXT Avon Yard discovered GATX 22278, a loaded UN 1814, Potassium Hydroxide, Solution, Class 8, PGII, tank car to have released product from the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Ashta Chemicals, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2018-05-28-00079. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined there was 1 manway bolt less than tool tight and the manway gasket was not installed correctly. As a preventative measure Sunpro opened the manway and correctly installed the gasket then secured the manway for transportation. NRC notification report 1213489. unable to enter in the appropriate box on page one.
column169: (NAR:208) CSX Hazmat discussed this issue with the shipper and stressed the importance of properly preparing a car for shipment.

column168: On May 31, 2018 at 1457 hours, CSX personnel at the Decatur, IL Yard reported a release from NATX 302882, a loaded Ethanol, UN1170, Class 3, PGII from the protective housing area.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Equistar Chemicals, LP was notified via Chemtrec, report number 2018-05-31-00310.  A CSX emergency response contractor, Sunpro was dispatched to the scene.  Upon inspection it was determined the sample line was partially open and the plug was not in place.  Sunpro closed the valve and secured the plug then cleaned the ethanol from the car. NRC notification made, report 1213827

column168: MATERIAL IS TRANSPORTED AS A SOLID. JUST BEFORE DELIVERY DISCHARGE AREA OF TANK STEAMED TO LOOSEN MATERIAL INTO A FREE FLOWING PRODUCT FOR REMOVAL FROM THE TANK. DURING THE HEATING OPERAION PRODUCT WAS NOTICED LEAKING FROM TOP OF THE TANK AND STEAMING OPERATION WAS HALTED IMMEDIATELY.  INITIAL INVESTIGATION APPEARS TO SHOW THAT LEAK IS COMING FROM A GASKET ON A BLIND-FLANGED PORT AT THE TOP OF THE ISO IN THE CRASH BOX. ONCE HEAT WAS REMOVED MATERIAL COOLED BACK INTO SOLID STATE AND LEAK STOPPED.  MITIGATION OF INCIDENT WAS ACCOMPLISHED THOROUGH PRIOR PREPARATION AS THE OPERATION AREA WAS DESIGNED TO CONTAIN WATER FROM STEAMING OPERATION OR OTHER LIQUIDS THEREBY CONTROLLING ANY SAFETY OR ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES WHICH ARISE DURING THE HEATING OPERATION.

column168: Unloading bulk Sodium Hypochlorite from rail stand #1  to storage tank #2 and failed to close hand valve at rail stand #3. Sodium Hypochlorite was pumped from rail stand #1 to rail stand #3 and exited transfer hose at rail stand #3. Sodium Hypochlorite discharged to ground at/around rail stand #3. Note: railcar did not fail, release caused by failure to properly close Sodium Hypochlorite plant transfer valve.   Description of the Accident (from first notification to termination of event)    8:15 AM - Plant worker Jeffrey Luckey, was unloading Sodium Hypochlorite 10.5 % by weight from rail car TILX 110424 from rail car stand #1 into storage tank #2. Approximately 30 minutes into the unloading process, Jeffrey Luckey noticed liquid beginning to pool under rail car stand #1.  Jeff immediately stopped unloading process by closing product discharge valve located atop rail car TILX 110424.   8:20 AM - Plant worker Jeff Luckey then called Jacksonville Plant Mgr David Schultz and informed him of the event.  David Shultz and Jeffrey Luckey walked to rail car stand # 3 and determined that the transfer valve at rail car stand #3 had been left open from the previous shift. Due to this open valve at rail car stand #3, product being off loaded from TILX 110424 at rail car stand #1, was inadvertently pumped through open valve at rail car stand #3 and exited rail car transfer hose found to have loosely fitted blind flange attached to hose end.  Product was pooled on the ground in the areas of rail cars stands #3, #2, #1.   8:25 AM - Plant Manager David Schultz then contacted Branch Manager Ky Nicholson and provided details of the event. Ky Nicholson then contacted by phone, Regional Manager Ron Zeigler and VP of Operations Todd Tucker and informed them of the event. Todd Tucker made calls as required to National Response Center (Rpt # 1212-311) and the Florida State Warning Point (Rpt # 2018-2990).   8:35 AM - Cliff Berry Inc Environmental Services contacted by Plant Manager Ky Nicholson                    Cliff Berry Area manager John Sandora dispatched to Jacksonville Plant   9:35-10:25 AM – FDEP Michael Holmes, CBI  Jon Sandora, and City of Jacksonville Helen Gainey/Terry Carr arrived to Jacksonville Plant.  Ky Nicholson updated them on event details and area affected by spillage was inspected. Cliff Berry Inc has been hired to mitigate areas affected by spillage.
column169: 1.     Modification of SOP to ensure valve closure is completed prior to unloading product 2. Review of the findings of this HMIR with all affected employees  3.     Modified the railcar startup/shutdown procedure to add that the valve that was left open during this incident must be checked and closed. 4.     A supervisor must visually inspect the startup and verify visually that it is correct before they offload. A supervisor must also visually inspect during the shutdown. The supervisor will sign off on these inspections.

column168: On 5/16/2018, aircraft on the ground (AOG) request from PHL to CLT for aircraft 976 for tool (controller, black base) which is non-hazardous.  The container that the tool (controller, black base) was in also contained dangerous goods tooling (fuel tank entry sniffer (UN3481)), two spare lithium batteries and two (UN1956) compressed gas cylinders.  The container with the non-hazardous tool (controller, black base) and the dangerous goods items, tooling (fuel tank entry sniffer), spare batteries and cylinders were inadvertently shipped undeclared on flight 1906 PHL/CLT on 5/16/2018.  The noncompliance was discovered when the box arrived at CLT Stores on 5/16/2018 and was opened, revealing the undeclared parts.   The PHL Shipper on record is current on hazmat training, and inadvertently, did not verify the contents of the container before shipping.
column169: The PHL Shipper responsible for shipping the container without verify the contents was coached and counseled,  made aware of the mistake and will be required to repeat hazardous materials training. Verification is underway to determine if there are any systemic issues and if corrective steps are necessary to prevent the apparent violation from recurring.

column168: Loving County- The driver of a semitrailer truck escaped critical injury early this Mother's Day (13-MAY-2018) morning after his truck spun out of control on County Road 300, about 6 miles north of Mentone, Texas..  Gregory R. Hines was traveling north on County Road 300 early Sunday, 13-MAY-2018, when his truck veered into the east shoulder and flipped over, said the Loving County Sheriff's Department officers that investigated the crash.  Hines is an employee of Plains Marketing, L. P. working out of the Pecos TX Truck District.  Hines was taken to the Winkler County Hospital by Winkler County EMS.  He was examined and evaluated there and subsequently released later that day. The cargo tank rupture allowed crude oil to leak onto an area of pasture east of the CR300 Right-of-Way where the semitrailer came to rest. Plains' Pecos Emergency Response Team contained the spill using containment booms, absorbents, and soil. Duration of the spill was approximately one hour. The cargo tank ruptures were circular breaches in the lower driver side quadrant of the tank shell, and tears rearward of the front bulkhead
column169: Immediately after receiving notification of the crash, at 1300 on 13-May-2018, Pecos Truck District management convened a safety stand down meeting for all drivers and reiterated Plains policies and guidance on distracted driving and overall safe driving practices.  Highlights of the directions are listed below. 1. Use your cell phone for emergency situations only. While you're driving, a cell phone should only be used for    emergency purposes. Even then, it's best to pull over safely to the right shoulder to make a call.  2. If you are drowsy, pull off the road. If you feel tired, get off the road; don't try to get home faster.  3. Limit the level of activity inside the vehicle.  Stay focused on the road rather than in-cab activities.  4. Avoid eating while driving.  Food spills are a major cause of distraction. 5. Do your multi-tasking outside the truck. Everyone spends a lot of time in their vehicles, and it may seem like the perfect time to get little things done: calling friends, searching for good music, maybe even text messaging. Don't do it. Focus on the road and the drivers around you. Get everything settled before you start driving. Take your time driving. The entire object is to keep yourself and your load safe on the road.

column168: JUST AFTER PUSH-BACK FROM GATE 51A AT LAX, A PASSENGERS VAPE PEN/BATTERY STARTED TO CATCH FIRE WHILE LOCATED UNDERNEATH THE SEAT, SCORCHING PASSENGERS BACKPACK AND CARPET OF THE AIRCRAFT IN THE AREA OF EVENT. VAPE PEN AND BATTERY WERE EXTINGUISHED USING A FIRE EXTINGUISHER ON-BOARD THE AIRCRAFT. AIRCRAFT RETURNED TO GATE AND WAS MET BY LAX FIRE DEPARTMENT. column42: CARBON DIOXIDE, SOLID OR DRY ICE
column168: HA Cargo Agent In Honolulu, assisted customer Clinical Labs as they were tendering four (4) shipments for to each of the  islands:  Hilo, Kona, Maui and Lihue.  At least one (1) piece for each island contained Dry Ice/UN1845.   HA Cargo Agent stated in her report she was unfamiliar with the process of accepting DG shipments,  so she asked her co-worker for assistance.  She asked her co-worker a few questions on what  needed to be done, so her co-worker advised her she needed to complete a Dry Ice Checklist for  each shipment, since all 4 shipments contained Dry Ice.  This is where the communication ended  between the two Agents.  Cargo Agent completing the checklist was unaware and did not know a NOPIC was needed for these  shipments containing Dry Ice.     The shipments for Kona and Maui went out to the flight line for departure.  The Kona shipment flew on HA398/23MAY18 with no NOPIC (AWB 04765331) .   As the Maui shipment was being uploaded to a flight, the Loading Ramp Agent noticed the DG stickers on the shipment and realized the article did not have a NOPIC.  The agent rejected the shipment and advised  the Cargo Runner of the reason why.  The Cargo Runner returned to the Cargo facility and notified  the office of the situation.  Cargo Agent that prepared the documents for the shipments was informed a NOPIC was needed for all Dry Ice shipments  and at that point she realized all the shipments she just processed did not have the required NOPIC.   The Cargo Agent confirmed with the Cargo Runner the shipments for Maui, Hilo and Lihue were still at the  Cargo facility, however the shipment for Kona (AWB 04765331) had already departed.    Cargo Agent immediately checked to ensure there were no AVIH on the same flight with the Kona  shipment and confirmed there was none.  One of the Office Agents assisted the Cargo Agent in completing a  NOPIC for each of the remaining shipments for Maui, Hilo and Lihue.
column169: Root causes of the incident are insufficient awareness of DG .     Awareness:  Cargo agent will need to be re-trained at the front counter and require proper guidance on the  correct procedure of identifying and accepting DG and  having an overall awareness.    Cargo Agent has been counseled on the correct steps/actions to follow when accepting DG.   Cargo Agent was reminded to seek assistance from a Supervisor or Manager when  it comes to questions regarding  accepting DG.

column168: On Thursday, May 24, 2018, Eli Lilly and Company received a cardboard box from the  US Postal Services at the Lilly Mail Hub (427 S. Illinois St, Indianapolis, IN 46285).    The Post Office employee mentioned the box had an odor.  A Lilly Contractor moved the box to  the Lilly X-Ray machine where the box was determined to contain 5 bottles.  The bottles were  not broken.  Based on the concerns of a potential chemical release, the Lilly Mail Hub contacted  the Lilly Fire/Rescue (LFR) for response.  LFR determined the package was labeled as containing  “tert-Butyl Isocyanide”.  In full respiratory protection, LFR opened the package, removed the  5 bottles, double wrapped the bottles in plastic, placed in plastic buckets, and surrounded the  items with absorbent.    Eli Lilly contacted the Post Office Inspector for Indianapolis, Ken Miller (317-945-7492), to  inform Post Office employees of potential exposure.    The package was sent via EMS SpeedPost from Conier Chem&Pharma Limited,  No 122 Honkong Street Kowloon,  Bay Lowloon Bay Horngjean HK, Hong Kong.    The chemical was identified on the shipping label.  The package contained 5 glass bottles  estimated at 0.5 L  in size.  The bottles were individually tapped shut at the cap and packaged in  bubble wrap.  The bubble wrapped bottles were placed in the box and surrounded with  Styrofoam peanuts.  Each bottle was approximately half full at time of repackaging.  The box  did not have any Hazardous Material Labels.  (See pictures in attached pdf)  The SDS identifies this chemical as a Hazardous Material with the transport information as  UN1992, Flammable Liquid, Toxic, N.O.S (2-Methylpropyl isocyanide), 3 (6.1), PG II.
column169: Eli Lilly notified Fisher Scientific (importer of record) of the incident.    Fisher contacted Conier Chem&Pharm to inform them of the issues.

column168: AT 17:00 HRS ON 5/7/18, IT WAS REPORTED THAT THE HAZMAT LOADED RAILCAR PROX 15174 WAS LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY COVER AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) RAIL YARD IN EAST ST. LOUIS IL. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND SECURE THE PACKAGE.  THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE LEAK ORIGINATING FROM THE LIQUID LINE CAP. THE CAP WAS REMOVED AND TEFLON TAPE APPLIED TO THE THREADS OF THE NTB FITTING. THE CAP WAS THEN REINSTALLED AND SECURED TOOL TIGHT. THE CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED AND THEN RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A ‘BULK’ SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. column168: TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH PRODUCT FOR DELIVERY TO A FARM. THE WEIGHT DISTRIBUTION ON THE TRAILER WAS INCORRECT, CAUSING INADEQUATE WEIGHT ON STEER TIRES OF THE TRUCK. DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF VEHICLE ON GRAVEL ROAD. TRUCK ENDED UP ON ITS SIDE IN ROAD DITCH AND THE TRAILER UPSIDE DOWN IN THE SAME DITCH. THE ICB CONTAINING THE ATRAZINE WAS PUNCTURED ON THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPILL. DRIVER CALLED HIS LOCATION MANAGER, AND THE LOCATION MANAGER HAD ADAM DEXTER CALL 911. LOCAL FIRE AND POLICE, STATE POLICE AND COMPANY PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO SCENE. THE LEAKING ICB WAS UP RIGHTED TO LIMIT THE RELEASE. COMPANY PERSONNEL THEN PUMPED SPILLED PRODUCT INTO ANOTHER ICB AND COVERED THE REMAINING PRODUCT WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. AFTER SITE WAS CLEARED OF VEHICLES AND PRODUCT, THE EFFECTED SOIL AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED AND SEEDED TO RESTORE THE SITE. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED AT 1:30PM THE SITE WAS CLEARED BY 7:30PM.
column169: THE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT WAS IMPROPER WEIGHT DISTRIBUTION ON THE TRAILER. ADDITIONAL TRAINING IS REQUIRED TO PROPERLY LOAD DELIVERY VEHICLES FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: During routine facility operations, a container was identified as having been compromised and to have released a small amount of its contents. In appropriate personal protective equipment, verified with internal health & safety professionals, the compromised container was safely over packed into a UN specification salvage drum authorized for this waste stream and the transport trailer was sufficiently decontaminated. No water ways, soil, land or storm drains were impacted; the release was contained to the transport trailer. Container was sent to its final destination without further incident. Although the released amount was under the reportable quantity, a courtesy call was reported to Mike McCain of the Washington State Department of Ecology. Mr. McCain indicated he would determine if it needed to be entered into their database, but never reported back if that was elected.
column169: An internal investigation began and a conversation with the generator with regard to container age and selection, was had. Driver was retrained on more thorough container inspection, to include examination of UN ratings.

column168: Container OOLU 156130 was found leaking in the Houston, TX intermodal facility on 5/16/2018.  After inspection it was verified that on 55 gallon steel drum was leaking due to a pin hole leak.  The cause of the pin hole was due to a nail puncturing the drum from the blocking and bracing.  The BNSF responder overpacked the damaged 55 gallon drum to mitigate the release.
column169: Ensure the shippers pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented as it relates to the securement and bracing of all drums before shipment.

column168: Multiple railcars were discovered leaking from the manways on Unit Train U-MNSGAT7-26A during a routine inspection by BNSF Mechanical forces.  Upon inspection it was discovered that 96 cars in this train were overloaded by volume (shell full).  A total of 22 cars experienced non-accident releases during the late afternoon and evening of 5/27/18.  The duration of the release is estimated at 4 hours and the volume is estimated at 50 gallons. The shipper should be contacted for questions regarding the overloaded condition of these cars.  The shipper contact is Robert Bauerle, his email is RBauerle@NuGenMarion.com and his phone is 605-941-6326.    BNSF dispatched hazardous materials responders and contractors to reduce the loads on these cars.  Approximately 1000-1200 gallons of product were removed from each car to obtain approximately 4% outage.  All leaks had ceased before BNSF responders arrived.  Questions on the response and mitigation can be addressed to the preparer of this report, Dillon Magers, dillon.magers@bnsf.com, cell phone 417 861 5396
column169: Shipper has reviewed their loading process and increased the outage from 2% to 5%.  BNSF will recover all train delay and contractor costs from the shipper.

column168: LTCX 1925 exhibited unusual venting from the valve cabinet upon arrival at Slaton, TX.  Photographs of the cabinet interior were provided to the shipper. column168: 6/1/18 ACCIDENT INFORMATION FROM 5/31/18: OUR DRIVER, MARVIN JACOBS WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON 1-10 CLOSE TO MM97 NEAR SCOTT, LA.  ANOTHER DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON I-10. THIS DRIVER CAME FROM THE WESTBOUND LANE, ACROSS THE GRASSY MEDIAN HEADING STRAIGHT FOR OUR DRIVER.  OUR DRIVER TOOK EVASIVE ACTION, MOVING SLIGHTLY TO THE RIGHT, TO PREVENT A HEAD COLLISION WITH THE OTHER DRIVER. THE OTHER DRIVER STRUCK OUR TRAILER AT THE DRIVER SIDE REAR AXLE WHICH COMPLETELY BROKE BOTH TRAILER AXLE OFF OF OUR TRAILER AND CAUSED OUR TRUCK AND TRAILER TO FALL OVER ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE. THE CYLINDERS CAME OFF OF THE TRAILER. THE CYLINDERS HAD CAPS ON THEM. THE POLICE CHIEF AND THE SALVAGE YARD THAT PICKED UP THE CYLINDERS REPORTED THAT THERE WAS NOT A RELEASE FROM ANY OF THE CYLINDERS.  NOTIFIED LA STATE POLICE AT 11:55 AMANDA GALLAGER 877-925-6595. REPORT #18-02518. SCOTT POLICE DEPARTMENT – OFFICER – J THACKER – POLICE REPORT #18-163565

column168: DRIVER WAS LOADING PROPANE TANKS ONTO FLATBED TRAILER WHEN ONE FEEL OFF AND BROKE OFF THE VALVE RELEASING THE PROPANE THAT WAS IN THE TANK. (APPROX 100 GALLONS) THE RELEASE WAS QUICK BUT THE OFFENSIVE ODOR-ANT (MERCAPTAN) THAT IS ADDED TO PROPANE IS A LINGERING BAD SMELL SO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CLOSED THE HIGHWAY FOR 1.5 HOURS TO MAKE SURE THERE WAS NOT A PROBLEM. PROPANE IS A NATURALLY OCCURRING GAS IN REGULAR AIR SO THE TANK WAS ALLOWED TO FINISH LEAKING AND THE PROBLEM WAS CONTAINED ALTHOUGH THE ODOR REMAINED.
column169: THE PROBLEM WAS HUMAN ERROR. THE DRIVER WAS LOADING A TANK THAT CONTAINED PROPANE AGAINST COMPANY POLICY. HE HAS BEEN TERMINATED. REFRESHER TRAINING FOR ALL CURRENT DRIVERS WAS CONDUCTED AND A NEW MODULE FOR LOAD SECUREMENT WAS DEVELOPED FOR FUTURE HIRES.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ON MAY 30, 2018, AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 A.M. CDT, A DRIVER WITH PREMIER FUEL DELIVERY SERVICE WAS OPERATING AT THE ABOVE-REFERENCED LOCATION WHEN THE DRIVER FELL ASLEEP AND LOST CONTROL OF THE TANKER UNIT. THE UNIT CROSSED THE MEDIAN AND ROLLED OVER. DUE TO THE ACCIDENT, THE 8,000 GALLON TANKER TRAILER WAS DAMAGED AND CAUGHT FIRE. IT WAS STATED THAT THE MAJORITY OF THE GASOLINE HAD BURNED AND THAT 1,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE HAD BEEN RELEASED TO THE SOIL SURFACE.
column169: ON MAY 30, 2018, AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 P.M. CDT, A REPRESENTATIVE WITH FEDERATED INSURANCE, MR. KURT KONOLD, RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES, L.C. (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP ON THEIR BEHALF. BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER CONTRACTED EMERGENCY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (EES) TO REMEDIATE THE SITE AS NECESSARY. EES WAS CONTACTED BY ARIZONA DOT AT TIME OF THE INCIDENT.  EES PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SITE AND CONDUCTED INITIAL REMEDIAL ACTIONS TO THE ROADWAY SURFACE AND SECURED THE SITE FOR EXCAVATION OF IMPACTED SOIL AT A LATER DATE. ON JUNE 5, 2018 THROUGH JUNE 15, 2018, EES PERSONNEL COMPLETED THE EXCAVATION OF THE GASOLINE-IMPACTED SOIL FROM THE SITE. ALL IMPACTED SOIL WAS CONTAINERIZED AND TRANSPORTED FOR DISPOSAL. SOIL SAMPLES THAT WERE COLLECTED FROM THE EXCAVATED AREA REFLECT THAT THE SITE REMEDIATION WAS SUCCESSFUL. EES PERSONNEL THEN BACK FILLED THE EXCAVATED AREA AND DEPLOYED SEED AND SOD TO THE BACK FILLED SITE.

column168: On Thurs 5/24@ 13:15 Hrs., the Savage Elko, NV Transload terminal incurred a 400 gal release of Ammonium nitrate, liquid(UN2426) from a Southwest Energy LLC tank car GATX 222232 that previously contained 18,332 gals, due to personnel not properly setting up said car to be sparged/bubbled. AN liquid tank cars need to be sparged/bubbled for effective even heating and to churn the product when changing it's stated from a solid to a liquid solution mixture to prevent salting and settled solids from accumulating. When setting up GATX 222232 for sparging from the car's Bottom Outlet Valve(BOV), the operator opened up the wrong tank car valve(e.g., liquid education line valve, rather than the air/vapor valve) in order to vent the car. Once pressure began to slowly build in the tank car, product began to discharge from the tank car's liquid education line valve, and cascaded down the sides of the car and accumulated in the track ballast and adjacent asphalt dive way. Once compressed air pressure was shutoff to the car, and the flow of product began to dissipate; terminal personnel then began emergency response initiatives, and notifications. Enviro Care(ER/Environmental Contractor) personnel responded to the scene, to clean-up the spill, remediate the affected area, clean GATX 222232 and estivate ballast and soil. No storm water and/or ground water was affected.
column169: The following corrective actions were implemented stemming from this incident: 1) A safety stand down was held with the entire Elko team to review this incident, along with the key leanings(e.g., cease rushing; how to properly identify vapor and liquid tank car valves, if in doubt exercise your stop work authority and immediately contact Mgmt., don't make assumptions; how to properly and safely sparge/bubble Ammonium nitrate, liquid tank cars)- Completed 5/25 2) The involved operator was provided coaching/counseling and issued performance improvement, with the emphasis of learning from this incident(e.g., cease rushing; how to properly identify vapor and liquid tank car valves, if in doubt exercise your stop work authority and immediately contact Mgmt., don't make assumptions; how to properly and safely sparge/bubble Ammonium nitrate, liquid tank cars)- Completed 6/5 I 3) Composed a pictorial procedure for safely sparging/bubbling tank cars which contain Ammonium nitrate, liquid; conduct corresponding training with the Elko team members on this procedure.- Completed 6/1

column168: On 05/30/2018 at 0200 EST ERTS received a call from Ben Artist concerning a spill that occurred at XPO Logistics(Terminal XDM) about a cargo release. It was reported that 110 pounds of hazardous UN1963 Helium Refrigerated Liquid was released unto the dock floor. Terminal Personnel reported that during unloading procedures on dock number 7, the cylinder(which was on wheels) had a wheel broken and due to the wheel not rolling properly, the cylinder tipped over and the spout on the cylinder broke releasing all contents into the air. Due to all of the materials escaping into the atmosphere,no waste was generated. XPO Will stage the empty cylinder in the OS&D.

column17: UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO. (ON BEHALF OF UPS FREIGHT, INC.)
column168: NOTE: UPS, Inc. is reporting this incident on behalf of UPS Freight, 1000 Semmes Avenue, Richmond, VA 23224. The DOT ID number and HM Registration numbers in this report are assigned to UPS Freight, not UPS, Inc. 4 pallets containing 45 cylinders of acetylene, dissolved with a gross weight of 9315 pounds were in a UPSF trailer that moved from TN to KY. The trailer was not opened in KY as it was scheduled to move the following morning(5/30/18) towards the final destination of CT. The UPSF driver in Lexington, KY hooked up to the placarded trailer(2.1 placards) and pulled it into the trailer repair shop to replace or remove a sticker. The mechanic could not remove the sticker with a scraper so he lit a hand-held butane torch to heat up the adhesive and remove the sticker. He was three feet from the trailer when he lit the torch which created an instant flash and explosion. The entire trailer and much of the shop was destroyed. The mechanic and driver were taken to the hospital with non life-threatening injuries and kept overnight for observation. Six other UPSF employees were taken to hospitals for medical treatment and evaluation. Those employees were released the same day. Formal notifications to NRC, PHMSA and OSHA. Apparently there was a leak from at least one of the cylinders which resulted in an accumulation of gas in the trailer as evidenced by the trajectory of the explosion- up, then out. A1145 cylinders were model WTL 224596 with cylinder tesVrequalification info of 03/2016 SF A507. Cylinder serial numbers are as follows: 226305, 110315, 216650, 152570, 109414, 197341, 133384, 202380, 060929, 224959, 208253, 216687, 226548, 153014, 115720, 225968, 110239, 224956, 201932, 202208, 108704, 220097, 174788, 226497, 201066, 022577, 200987, 183402,002833,178824,169693,219771,059889,249364,209173,226651,200984,126859,224074,176895,152628,

column168: Driver Guy Harris did follow delivery procedures or 90% rule for safe delivery. Driver did not sticks the product tanks to confirm safe tank fill, did not connect vapor recovery hose from vapor fill to trailer vapor connection, while dropping regular gasoline product into regular tank#T2 fill without placing back fill caps on regular tanks #Tl and #T3 and without vapor recovery hose hooked up causing back pressure in product tanks pushing up regular gasoline up and out regular tank fill#Tl with fill caps not secured to fill pipes#Tl&#T3. After the driver notice the regular gasoline flowing up fill pipe#Tl and flowing onto the pavement and onto McLane Ave. he shutdown the delivery. Resulting in a 200 gallon gasoline spill on Sunoco station 931 McLane Ave. Yonkers Ave. New York 10704.

column168: On 05/31/2018 at 0830 hours. personnel in the CSXT Ashtabula Yard discovered GATX 60775, a residue tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the National Response Center, Ohio EPA, Federal Railroad Administration and Shipper were notified.(CHEMTREC Report #2018-0531-00099). SUNPRO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line and vapor line secondary closure flange with multiple less than tool tight securement bolts. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, USALCO, Mr. Craig Owen, phone 443-571-6315. Contractor personnel secured all secondary closure securement bolts without incident. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required? Cause Code: 242 NARRI: 90

column168: Driver ran off of roadway and overturned, slammed a rock embankment, causing the tanker to break into 2 sections creating the spill.  The HM response team was contacted immediately. column168: HAZMAT DRIVER WAS AT A TA TRUCK STOP IN BREEZEWOOD, PA GETTING REPAIRS MADE TO AIR BAG WHEN THE MECHANIC NOTICED MATERIAL DRIPPING FROM UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER FLOOR NEAR THE FRONT AXLE. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE 25 GAL. FIBER DRUM ON A PALLET WAS LEAKING INSIDE THE BOX VAN TRAILER AND THE WOODEN TRAILER FLOOR BECAME COMPROMISED ALLOWING MATERIAL TO PENETRATE. THE TRAILER WAS BOUGHT OUTSIDE AND BUCKET PLACED UNDERNEATH THE SOURCE. MATERIAL WAS DRIPPING OUT AT A SLOW PACE, APPROX. 1 DRIP EVERY 8-10 MINUTES. HAZMAT ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP, INC. CONTACTED EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY, HAZ-MAT ONE, TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. THE 25 GAL. CONTAINER WAS OVERPACKED IN A 55-GAL. POLY DRUM AND ONE 30-GAL DRUM OF SPILL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS GENERATED. BOTH DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK ON THE TRAILER AND TAKEN TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: IT HAS BEEN SUGGESTED TO THE SHIPPER TO CONSIDER USING POLY DRUMS VS.  FIBER DRUMS WHICH WOULD CONTAIN/SUSTAIN SULFURIC ACID MATERIAL IN THE EVENT THE INNER PLASTIC LINER FAILED.  RECOMMENDATION:  POLY DRUM SHOULD BE USED FOR ANY ACID MATERIAL. IN THIS CASE, ALTHOUGH THE SHIPPING DESCRIPTION WAS "CORROSIVE SOLIDS", THE MATERIAL WAS A GEL LIKE SUBSTANCE AND HEAT (HIGH TEMPS) COULD HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE BREAKDOWN OF THE GEL, TRANSFORMING IT INTO A LIQUID STATE.

column168: DRIVER WAS DRIVING NORTHBOUND ON HIGHWAY 63, 3 MILES SOUTH OF HOUSTON, MO WHEN HE STRUCK A GUARDRAIL/BRIDGE WITH THE TRACTOR/ TRIAL RIGHT SIDE. THIS CAUSED THE COMPARTMENT #3 VALVE AND PIPING ON THE TRAILER TO BREAK CAUSING A SPILL OF 1,132 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE ON TO THE ROADWAY AND SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY. 911 WAS CONTACTED. MO HIGHWAY PATROL AND THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT. WE CONTACTED OUR INSURANCE COMPANY, AND THEY CONTACTED SUNBELT ENVIRONMENTAL TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL. INSURANCE CLAIM #4134997, INSURANCE CLAIMS ADJUSTER MARLIN ZECHMAN, PHONE # 1-484-467-4075. MO DNR RESPONDED REP.- KEN HANON, 573-634-2436
column169: AFTER INVESTIGATING THE ACCIDENT, WE DETERMINED THE DRIVER WAS DISTRACTED. THAT CAUSED HIM TO STRIKE THE GUARDRAIL AND BRIDGE. THE DRIVER'S EMPLOYMENT WAS TERMINATED. WE PROVIDE INTIAL AND ONGOING SAFETY TRAINING ON SAFE DRIVING TECHNIQUES INCLUDING: 1. NOT DRIVING DISTRACTED 2. OBEYING SPEED LIMIT LAWS 3. NOT DRIVING ILL OR FATIGUED 4. DEFENSIVE DRIVING

column168: DRIVER WAS OFF-LOADING DIESEL INTO AN ABOVE GROUND TANK UTILIZING A PUMP SYSTEM FROM DELIVERY TRUCK TO STATIONARY TANK AT GAS STATION. DRIVER NOTICED WHEN TURNING ON THE PUMP A DRIP COMING FROM ONE OF THE ALUMINUM TRANSFER LINES UNDER THE TRUCK. THIS LEAK WAS COMING FROM A WELD BETWEEN TO OF THE LINES. DRIVER TURNED OFF THE PUMP AND PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE LINE TO STOP ANY FURTHER DAMAGE. AN ESTIMATED 5 GALLONS OF DIESEL MADE CONTACT WITH THE DIRT.  *** NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO WASHINGTON ENIVRONMENTAL CASE #ERTS689302 REP. CURT PIESCH PHONE 360-607-3736  *** NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO DEQ REPORT #19-1662
column169: TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN IN THE FUTURE WE HAVE DONE THE FOLLOWING:  1. PROVIDED EXTRA TRAINING TO ALL DRIVERS WITH REGARDS TO CORRECT PUMP OPERATIONS WITH AN EMPHASIS ON MAKING SURE DRIVERS EXAM THE PIPING FROM PUMP TO TANK.  2. THIS TRUCK HAD JUST RECEIVED THE TANK TEST. WE HAVE CONTACTED THE TESTING COMPANY AND INFORMED THEM OF THE INCIDENT AND REQUESTED VERIFICATION CHECKS OF THE TUBING AS THE LEAK CAME FROM A WELD CONNECTING TWO PIPES. THIS WAS AN ORIGINAL WELD FROM THE MANUFACTURER, THE TANK OR PIPING HAS NEVER BEEN WELDED ON OUTSIDE OF ORIGINAL MANUFACTURE.   3. THE FUEL DROPPED ON AN AREA OF DIRT WHERE THE CONNECTION TO THE ABOVE GROUND TANKS ARE LOCATED. DURING CLEAN-UP TESTING IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE GROUND MUST HAVE BEEN CONTAMINATED PRIOR ALONG TIME AGO AS THE CLEAN-UP CREW HAD TO GO OVER 3 FEET TO GET TO UNCONTAMINATED SOIL. THIS OBVIOUSLY WAS NOT FROM A 5 GALLON SPILL THAT WE CALLED TO HAVE CLEANED IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AS OUR DRIVER PLACED ABSORBENT PADS DOWN IMMEDIATELY. WE ARE REVIEWING OUR POLICIES FOR TAKING ON NEW CONTRACTS TO IDENTIFY LOCATIONS WITH SOIL AND OUR ABILITY TO TEST THE AREA PRIOR TO OUR TAKING THE CONTRACT.  OVERALL WE IMPROVED OUR OPERATING PROCEDURES.
